Models - basic ones

Function that allows to calculate the root mean square error so that we can see which model is the most effective on predicting the energy appliances.

rmse <- function(yp, y) {
  return(sqrt(mean((yp - y)^2)))
}

We make a PCA to visualize the variables correlation and identify homogeneous or in the opposite identify specific hidden profiles.

fviz_pca_var(res.pca,col.var = "black")

From this grah, we can notice that we dont even see rv1 and rv2 arrows. We can also note that lights and visibility are poorly represented but also not correlated. Thats why we decided to remove rv1, rv2, lights and visibility from the features.

We can clearly observe the efficiency of the Random Forest model since it has the lowest RMSE. We can now try to find the appropriate hyperparameters to tune the model so that it is even more accurate.

Tuning the model

To tune the hyperparameters of the random forest, we focus on mtry, and search for its optimal value (with respect to Out-Of-Bag OOB error estimate). We use the tuneRF function.

bestmtry <- tuneRF(data, data$Appliances, stepFactor = 1.2, improve = 0.01, trace=T, plot= T)
